2026-04-16 12:33:22 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor module relay contacts', 'ambient sensor module internal drive circuitry around relay'] hypothesis_explanation='The power supply module clearly provides proper 12 V (its LED is on). The load module was initially able to light the lamp, so the lamp, indicator bulb, and series diode are likely functional.\n\nThe key diagnostic is the voltage measurement at the ambient sensor (control) module output while the lamp should be ON: only about 0.36 V appears between the module’s output + and − relative to its correctly‑polarized input. This means that, even under conditions where the relay should be closed (dark room), the control module is not passing the 12 V through to the load. The earlier symptom of the lamp cycling off briefly every ~20 s is also consistent with a failing relay or its drive circuit intermittently opening the supply, then degrading further until it no longer closes at all.\n\nSince the input from the power supply to the control module must be present (otherwise the lamp would never have lit and the control electronics could not operate), the fault is localized inside the ambient sensor module, between its input and output—most plausibly:\n- Welded, burned, or high‑resistance relay contacts, or\n- Failed relay coil / driver circuitry so the relay never properly energizes.\n\nReplacing/repairing the relay and associated drive circuitry in the ambient sensor (control) module should restore a solid 12 V output to the load when the sensor commands ON, eliminating the flicker and current absence.'
