2026-04-16 12:34:32 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module output connector / wiring on + line (including PCB pad, crimp, and cable)', 'control module internal current-sense / indicator branch loading the + output node'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show ~12 V available up to the relay output and sensor-bias resistor, but only ~0.36 V appears at the Control Output (+) cable on both the control and load sides, with the − line essentially at 0 V. Replacements of the relay contacts and any deliberate series-output component did not change this behavior, and internal − rail is only slightly elevated (0.12–0.36 V), so the dominant voltage loss is not in the return path.\n\nThis points to a fault localized right at or immediately after the + output node: either (1) a high-resistance/open connection at the PCB pad, crimp, or conductor of the Control Output (+) wiring, creating a large series resistance that drops nearly all the 12 V under even small load; and/or (2) an unintended load to ground from the module’s own indicator / current-sense branch that is tied to the output node and is partially shorted or damaged, clamping the node around a few hundred millivolts while the relay feeds it through the high-resistance joint.\n\nBecause the earlier diagnostic test showed that the voltage has already collapsed to ~0.36 V at the pad where the output cable attaches, yet upstream nodes remain at ~12 V, the fault must involve the immediate output connection or an internal branch from that exact node, not the relay, not the deliberate series component, and not the external wiring polarity. Repair should therefore focus on the Control Output (+) connector/wiring and any indicator or sensing circuitry directly connected to that node.'
